1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:05,320
If you are a scalper, then you DEFINITELY 
must try out this scalping strategy! No  

2
00:00:05,320 --> 00:00:11,560
indicators, no lag, just pure price action!
 
So… we’ll look for signals on the 1-minute  

3
00:00:11,560 --> 00:00:18,000
timeframe, using only price action and some basic 
smart money concepts, like liquidity, supply  

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:24,520
and demand zones, and breaks of structure. 
 
The first setup focuses on a specific pattern:  

5
00:00:24,520 --> 00:00:31,560
an institutional candle followed by at least 
8 inside bars, ideally 10 small candles,  

6
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:35,080
forming a tight channel.
The trade is triggered when  

7
00:00:35,080 --> 00:00:40,960
the price breaks out of this channel range.
The institutional bar is the setup candle,  

8
00:00:40,960 --> 00:00:47,280
a larger price bar that sets the initial range.
Inside bars are the following smaller bars,  

9
00:00:47,280 --> 00:00:51,160
that form within the high and 
low of the institutional bar. 
  

10
00:00:51,160 --> 00:00:55,920
When you see 8 or more inside bars, 
it shows the market is consolidating. 

11
00:00:55,920 --> 00:01:03,160
I use this indicator to find inside bars.
 
Now, this setup creates a channel on your chart. 

12
00:01:03,160 --> 00:01:08,280
The top of the channel is the institutional 
bar's high, and the bottom is its low. 

13
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:14,360
The inside bars stay within this range, 
making the market look calm for a bit. 

14
00:01:14,360 --> 00:01:17,920
The key is to wait for a 
breakout from this channel. 

15
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:22,920
This shows increasing momentum, that 
could lead to a decent scalping move.
  

16
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:28,520
For a buy trade, you'd enter when the 
price breaks above the channel's top. 

17
00:01:28,520 --> 00:01:33,200
For a sell trade, you'd enter 
when it breaks below the bottom. 

18
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:37,320
The scalping plan here is that 
after this tight consolidation,  

19
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:43,680
the market is ready to make a bigger move.
 
Now, this scalping approach only works in  

20
00:01:43,680 --> 00:01:49,000
combination with support and resistance 
levels, or supply and demand levels. 

21
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:52,920
These areas help you find 
good spots to enter trades. 

22
00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:56,680
When the price breaks out of 
the channel, near a key support  

23
00:01:56,680 --> 00:02:02,440
or demand level, it's a stronger signal.
This means you have two reasons to take the  

24
00:02:02,440 --> 00:02:09,000
trade - the breakout and the level itself.
And when trading this setup, you also  

25
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:15,960
pay attention to the overall market context.
Is the market in a broader uptrend, or downtrend? 

26
00:02:15,960 --> 00:02:21,600
This can help you decide which breakout 
direction is more likely to succeed. 

27
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:26,760
For exits, you can use minor levels.
You look for small areas where the  

28
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:33,680
price has paused, or reversed before.
These can be good spots to take profits.
 
  

29
00:02:33,680 --> 00:02:39,280
This scalping setup is a classic example 
of trend continuation, showing how markets  

30
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:45,680
move in cycles of contraction and expansion.
Big market players use these cycles to build  

31
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:52,120
positions, and profit from market moves.
The ideal signal looks like this: a strong  

32
00:02:52,120 --> 00:02:59,320
upward move, followed by a period of contraction 
(the institutional candle and the inside bars),  

33
00:02:59,320 --> 00:03:05,920
ideally at a demand level, then a 
breakout continuing the upward trend. 
  

34
00:03:05,920 --> 00:03:11,720
This is how smart money operates in the market.
The initial upward move (the institutional  

35
00:03:11,720 --> 00:03:17,880
candle) is driven by big players.
They buy steadily, pushing the price up. 

36
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:22,920
But they can't buy forever without 
causing the price to spike too quickly. 

37
00:03:22,920 --> 00:03:27,920
So they pause, creating the 
contraction phase we see on the chart. 

38
00:03:27,920 --> 00:03:33,120
During this contraction, the institutional 
candle sets the range, and the following  

39
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:40,400
inside bars show decreasing volatility. 
 
This is not random. Smart money is using  

40
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:45,640
this time to continue building their 
position, without alerting other traders. 

41
00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:49,680
The longer the contraction lasts, 
the more tension builds up. 

42
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:56,320
This tension is what fuels the eventual breakout.
That’s why I want at least 8 inside bars,  

43
00:03:56,320 --> 00:04:00,200
preferably over 10.
 
The contraction phase also  

44
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:07,360
serves another purpose for smart money: it creates 
a zone where other traders place their orders. 

45
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:14,440
Breakout traders put buy orders above the range, 
thinking they'll catch the move when it starts. 

46
00:04:14,440 --> 00:04:20,200
Short-term traders might place 
sell orders, betting on a reversal. 

47
00:04:20,200 --> 00:04:25,360
Smart money sees all these orders 
as potential fuel for the next move. 

48
00:04:25,360 --> 00:04:30,040
When they're ready, they push the 
price up, triggering these orders. 

49
00:04:30,040 --> 00:04:34,240
The breakout traders' buy orders 
add to the upward momentum. 

50
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:41,040
The short sellers' stop losses get hit, forcing 
them to buy, and pushing the price even higher.
  

51
00:04:41,040 --> 00:04:45,440
This is the expansion phase. This is 
when we enter! The built-up tension  

52
00:04:45,440 --> 00:04:51,480
is released, and the price moves quickly.
Ideally, the candles after the breakout are  

53
00:04:51,480 --> 00:04:56,640
larger, showing increased volatility.
This is the market expanding  

54
00:04:56,640 --> 00:05:01,120
after the contraction.
 
For us, scalpers, this pattern  

55
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:05,880
offers several potential entry points.
You could buy the breakout when price  

56
00:05:05,880 --> 00:05:12,000
closes above the institutional bar's high.
Or you could wait for a slight pullback  

57
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:17,880
after the breakout, which often happens 
as some traders take quick profits. 

58
00:05:17,880 --> 00:05:23,200
The stop loss for this trade could go 
below the low of the contraction phase. 

59
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:28,160
If price falls below this level, 
it might mean the move has failed. 

60
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:32,800
As for targets, look at the size 
of the move before the contraction. 

61
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:38,360
Breakouts often move about the same 
distance as the prior trend wave. 
  

62
00:05:38,360 --> 00:05:44,640
So to find a “sell” scalping signal on the 
1 minute chart, you look for these elements: 

63
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:51,680
First, identify a strong downtrend on the chart. 
You want to see a series of lower highs and lower  

64
00:05:51,680 --> 00:05:57,800
lows, confirming the bearish sentiment.
Next, find the institutional candle,  

65
00:05:57,800 --> 00:06:03,680
followed by 8 or more inside bars, 
creating a tight trading range. 

66
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:08,800
This consolidation is basically a pause 
in the downtrend, where buyers and  

67
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:14,520
sellers are temporarily in balance.
Pay close attention to how price  

68
00:06:14,520 --> 00:06:19,920
behaves at the bottom of this range.
If it struggles to make new lows, or  

69
00:06:19,920 --> 00:06:26,560
repeatedly tests and fails at the lower boundary, 
this could be a sign of temporary strength. 

70
00:06:26,560 --> 00:06:31,960
But remember, we're looking for a 
continuation of the downtrend, not a reversal. 

71
00:06:31,960 --> 00:06:38,680
A short signal would trigger if price breaks 
down, below the low of the institutional candle. 

72
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:44,040
This breakdown should come with 
increased volume and larger red candles. 

73
00:06:44,040 --> 00:06:47,760
For confirmation, you can 
wait for a small pullback. 

74
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:55,120
You're essentially looking for a weak attempt at 
an upward move, that fails to gain traction.
 
 
  

75
00:06:55,120 --> 00:07:02,040
This chart shows a classic buy signal in an 
uptrend, with price reacting at a demand zone. 

76
00:07:02,040 --> 00:07:07,960
First, we see a clear uptrend, marked 
by higher highs and higher lows. 

77
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:12,840
The uptrend sets the stage for our 
buy signal, as it's often best to  

78
00:07:12,840 --> 00:07:18,200
trade in the direction of the main trend.
The support zone, which can also be found  

79
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:24,680
on a higher time frame, is very important here.
It was a previous resistance level, that price  

80
00:07:24,680 --> 00:07:29,520
broke through earlier in the uptrend.
Once price breaks above resistance,  

81
00:07:30,320 --> 00:07:36,840
that level often becomes new support.
 
Notice how price reacts at the support level. 

82
00:07:36,840 --> 00:07:38,960
We have our institutional candle,  

83
00:07:38,960 --> 00:07:44,720
followed by consecutive inside bars, 
showing a contraction in volatility. 

84
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:50,640
The buy signal comes when we see a bullish 
candle forming above this contraction. 

85
00:07:50,640 --> 00:07:56,800
Considering all these factor, it means 
buyers stepping in strongly at support,  

86
00:07:56,800 --> 00:08:04,440
during an overall uptrend. Buyers took control 
and preventing prices from falling lower.
  

87
00:08:04,440 --> 00:08:09,320
A buy scalping signal must be 
strengthened by several factors: 

88
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:13,080
First, it must be in line 
with the overall uptrend. 

89
00:08:13,080 --> 00:08:17,440
It should appear at a clear 
support level or demand area. 

90
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:23,240
And the institutional candle must 
have many consecutive inside bars. 

91
00:08:23,240 --> 00:08:29,200
This scalping approach aligns with the principle 
that it's usually best to trade with the trend. 

92
00:08:29,200 --> 00:08:35,040
In an uptrend, we look for opportunities 
to buy on pullbacks or corrections. 

93
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:59,440
And a demand area provides exactly 
that kind of opportunity.
 
 
 
 
 

94
00:10:00,360 --> 00:10:02,920
Now, not all breakouts are real. 

95
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:06,920
Sometimes, the price might make 
a false move outside the channel,  

96
00:10:06,920 --> 00:10:11,280
and then quickly come back in.
This is called a false breakout,  

97
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:17,200
and often happens with a pin bar, a 
candle with a "wick" outside the channel. 

98
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:20,760
This is the second variation 
of this scalping approach. 

99
00:10:20,760 --> 00:10:26,960
When a pin bar happens, it's actually a good 
chance to trade in the opposite direction.
  

100
00:10:26,960 --> 00:10:31,200
So this chart shows a false 
breakout to the downside. 

101
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:36,320
The price made a quick move below the 
channel, but then came right back in. 

102
00:10:36,320 --> 00:10:41,120
This is a signal to buy when the 
price retraces inside the channel. 

103
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:45,440
You see, false breakouts are often 
liquidity sweeps in disguise. 

104
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:51,000
Big players use false breakouts to 
trap traders and create liquidity. 

105
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:56,600
The institutional bar, followed by 
the inside bars, create a tight range. 

106
00:10:56,600 --> 00:11:03,200
This range acts like a magnet for orders.
Traders place buy orders above, and sell orders  

107
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:07,960
below, thinking they'll catch the breakout.
But smart money sees these  

108
00:11:07,960 --> 00:11:13,360
orders as liquidity pools.
 
When price breaks out of the range,  

109
00:11:13,360 --> 00:11:19,520
often times against the prevailing trend, 
it's often not a real move. It's a trick. 

110
00:11:19,520 --> 00:11:24,360
Big players push the price just 
far enough to trigger these orders. 

111
00:11:24,360 --> 00:11:28,880
They're not trying to start a new 
trend. They're hunting for liquidity.
  

112
00:11:28,880 --> 00:11:33,440
In this particular case, we 
see an upward false breakout. 

113
00:11:33,440 --> 00:11:36,520
The price moves above the 
range, but it doesn't stay  

114
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:43,800
there. This quick move up is the liquidity sweep.
Observe the institutional candle, the inside bars,  

115
00:11:43,800 --> 00:11:50,560
and then the pin bar, completing the pattern.
 
 
This inducement is designed to do 2 things: 

116
00:11:50,560 --> 00:11:55,880
First, it triggers buy orders from 
breakout traders. They see the price  

117
00:11:55,880 --> 00:12:02,480
rise and think a big move up is starting.
Second, it hits the stop losses of traders  

118
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:06,960
who sold near the top of the range. 
They thought price would go down,  

119
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:12,480
but now their stops are getting hit.
All these actions create a pool of liquidity. 

120
00:12:12,480 --> 00:12:17,760
And that's exactly what smart money wants.
They use this liquidity to enter short  

121
00:12:17,760 --> 00:12:22,320
positions at good prices.
 
 
The key is waiting to see what  

122
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:28,880
happens next. Price doesn't keep rising. 
Instead, it snaps back into the range. 

123
00:12:28,880 --> 00:12:33,360
This is the "immediate retrace" 
we see on the chart. It's a clear  

124
00:12:33,360 --> 00:12:39,080
sign that the breakout was false.
This retrace is smart money selling.  

125
00:12:39,080 --> 00:12:43,920
They're using all that liquidity from 
the sweep to enter their positions. 

126
00:12:43,920 --> 00:12:47,800
Now they have the fuel they 
need to push price lower. 

127
00:12:47,800 --> 00:12:52,800
For us, scalpers, this false 
breakout is a selling opportunity. 

128
00:12:52,800 --> 00:13:00,160
When we see price retrace back into the channel, 
after that quick rise, it's our signal to sell. 

129
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:04,720
We're essentially trading with smart 
money, taking advantage of all those  

130
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:12,480
traders who got tricked by the false breakout.
 
But why does this work? It's all about order flow! 

131
00:13:12,480 --> 00:13:16,640
Markets need a balance of 
buyers and sellers to move. 

132
00:13:16,640 --> 00:13:23,160
If everyone's buying, who are they buying from? 
If everyone's selling, who are they selling to? 

133
00:13:23,160 --> 00:13:27,000
Smart money uses these sweeps 
to create that balance.
  

134
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:31,640
Think of it like this: If smart 
money wants to buy a lot of orders,  

135
00:13:31,640 --> 00:13:36,240
they need someone to sell to them.
But if the market looks bullish,  

136
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:40,680
not many people want to sell.
So they create a scenario that  

137
00:13:40,680 --> 00:13:47,280
encourages selling. That's our false breakout.
Once they have these sellers, they can buy.
  

138
00:13:47,280 --> 00:13:52,320
This concept of liquidity is crucial 
in understanding market moves. 

139
00:13:52,320 --> 00:13:56,520
Price doesn't just move up or 
down randomly. It moves to where  

140
00:13:56,520 --> 00:14:04,320
there are orders. These orders are liquidity.
And smart money is always looking for liquidity. 

141
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:08,320
In this scalping strategy, 
we're not just looking at price. 

142
00:14:08,320 --> 00:14:14,280
We're looking at the story behind the price.
We're trying to spot these liquidity sweeps. 

143
00:14:14,280 --> 00:14:21,080
When we see a tight range form, we get ready. We 
know smart money might try to sweep that range.
 
  

144
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:26,520
And remember our first approach, not 
every breakout is false. Sometimes,  

145
00:14:26,520 --> 00:14:32,080
price really does start a new trend.
That's why we wait for the retrace.  

146
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:38,800
We need confirmation that the breakout 
was indeed a sweep, not a real move.
 
  

147
00:14:38,800 --> 00:14:45,600
This chart shows a buy signal in an uptrend, 
with price reacting at a key support level. 

148
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:51,040
We see a clear uptrend, marked 
by higher highs and higher lows. 

149
00:14:51,040 --> 00:14:55,080
The uptrend sets the stage for 
our buy signal, as we aim to  

150
00:14:55,080 --> 00:15:00,560
trade in the direction of the order flow.
The support level is crucial here. It was  

151
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:06,040
a previous resistance level, that price 
broke through earlier in the uptrend. 

152
00:15:06,040 --> 00:15:10,040
Then we see price pull back to 
test this new support level. 

153
00:15:10,040 --> 00:15:14,640
Notice how price reacts at the level. 
We see an institutional candle,  

154
00:15:14,640 --> 00:15:19,000
and a series of small bars 
forming just above support. 

155
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:23,440
These are inside bars, showing 
a contraction in volatility. 

156
00:15:23,440 --> 00:15:28,960
The buy signal comes when we see a wick outside 
the channel, followed by an immediate retrace. 
  

157
00:15:30,240 --> 00:15:36,160
This is a classic sign of a liquidity sweep.
Price briefly drops below the support level,  

158
00:15:36,160 --> 00:15:41,240
triggering stop losses of weak longs.
Smart money quickly buys up these  

159
00:15:41,240 --> 00:15:44,760
orders, at a discount.
And price immediately  

160
00:15:44,760 --> 00:15:49,840
retraces back into the trading range.
This price action suggests strong  

161
00:15:49,840 --> 00:15:53,840
buying pressure at support.
It's a sign that big players  

162
00:15:53,840 --> 00:15:59,240
are possibly accumulating positions, 
setting up for the next move higher. 

163
00:15:59,240 --> 00:16:05,800
The next bar is our entry signal. This bar 
closes firmly inside the trading range,  

164
00:16:05,800 --> 00:16:11,920
confirming that the drop below support 
was just a trap for weak hands.
 

165
00:16:11,920 --> 00:16:19,840
Any buy signal after an institutional candle and a 
pin bar, must be strengthened by several factors: 

166
00:16:19,840 --> 00:16:23,920
First, it must in line with 
the overall order flow. 

167
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:31,520
Then it must be at a clear support level, with 
several touches, or at an unmitigated demand area. 

168
00:16:31,520 --> 00:16:37,760
And the quick rejection of lower prices 
must confirm the buying pressure.
 
 
  

169
00:16:37,760 --> 00:16:44,040
Let's look at another case, a short signal.
First, we see a clear downtrend, marked by  

170
00:16:44,040 --> 00:16:48,440
lower highs and lower lows.
So this downtrend sets  

171
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:54,280
the stage for our short signal.
And here notice this supply zone. Which  

172
00:16:54,280 --> 00:17:01,480
is unmitigated, has not been touched before.
We see price rally up to test this area. This  

173
00:17:01,480 --> 00:17:08,320
rally is normal and healthy in a downtrend.
Notice how price reacts at the supply zone. 

174
00:17:08,320 --> 00:17:13,120
We have an institutional candle, 
then a series of small bars. 

175
00:17:13,120 --> 00:17:20,040
The short signal comes when we see a wick 
outside the channel, and an immediate retrace. 

176
00:17:20,040 --> 00:17:25,800
This is the liquidity sweep we need. Price 
briefly spikes above the resistance level,  

177
00:17:25,800 --> 00:17:31,800
triggering stop losses of weak shorts.
Smart money quickly sells into this rally,  

178
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:35,160
trapping late buyers.
And price immediately  

179
00:17:35,160 --> 00:17:40,560
retraces back into the trading range.
This price action suggests strong selling  

180
00:17:40,560 --> 00:17:44,440
pressure at a supply zone.
It's a sign that big players  

181
00:17:44,440 --> 00:17:50,680
are setting up for the next move lower.
As the next candle closes firmly inside the  

182
00:17:50,680 --> 00:17:57,800
trading range, it confirms that the spike above 
the channel was just a trap for weak hands.
 
  

183
00:17:57,800 --> 00:18:04,360
Another signal. This short signal is valid, 
because it’s strengthened by multiple factors: 

184
00:18:04,360 --> 00:18:09,000
It's in line with the overall downtrend,
It's at a clear resistance level  

185
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:12,200
with multiple touches,
And the quick rejection  

186
00:18:12,200 --> 00:18:19,320
of higher prices shows strong selling pressure.
For the entry, you could short as the "liquidity  

187
00:18:19,320 --> 00:18:28,760
sweep" bar closes. The stop loss could go 
just above the wick of the previous bar.
 
  

188
00:19:46,120 --> 00:19:50,360
Now, what if you don’t have an 
institutional candle to trade? 

189
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:54,240
Well, another variation of this 
scalping method is when you first  

190
00:19:54,240 --> 00:20:00,240
spot a pin bar, and then an inside bar.
So first you have a pin bar, with a long  

191
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:06,480
tail and a small body, rejecting a level.
For a real pin bar, the tail must be at  

192
00:20:06,480 --> 00:20:11,880
least 50% of the bar's total range.
The longer the tail (or the wick),  

193
00:20:11,880 --> 00:20:17,000
the stronger the pin bar signal. 
 
Candles with long wicks are great for  

194
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:21,600
scalping, because they help you 
spot possible market reversals. 

195
00:20:21,600 --> 00:20:25,640
When pin bars form, it often means 
the market might move in the opposite  

196
00:20:25,640 --> 00:20:30,520
direction, at least for a short while.
The opportunity comes when the next  

197
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:37,600
candle's range, fits inside the pin bar’s range.
So the high and low of the second candle are  

198
00:20:37,600 --> 00:20:44,680
completely within the first candle's range.
 
This is the pin bar – inside bar combo. 

199
00:20:44,680 --> 00:20:50,560
So you look for a candle with a long wick, 
at a key support or resistance level, 

200
00:20:50,560 --> 00:20:54,880
You wait for an inside bar to 
form right after the pin bar, 

201
00:20:54,880 --> 00:20:58,600
And you enter the trade when the 
price breaks out of the inside bar,  

202
00:20:59,200 --> 00:21:03,720
in the direction of the pin bar.
 
 
Here’s a bullish setup: 

203
00:21:03,720 --> 00:21:11,840
The pin bar forms at a demand zone (or support). 
This long lower wick shows strong buying pressure. 

204
00:21:11,840 --> 00:21:17,600
It's like buyers rushing in to grab a 
good deal when the price dips too low. 

205
00:21:17,600 --> 00:21:24,160
The inside bar that follows is a pause.
Buyers and sellers are sizing each other up,  

206
00:21:24,160 --> 00:21:29,640
waiting to see who'll make the next move.
When price breaks above the pin bar’s high,  

207
00:21:29,640 --> 00:21:34,640
it implies demand has won out.
Buyers are pushing the price up,  

208
00:21:34,640 --> 00:21:41,200
and some sellers might be closing their 
losing trades, adding more upward pressure.
  

209
00:21:41,200 --> 00:21:44,640
For a bearish setup:
The pin bar forms at a  

210
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:51,560
supply zone (or resistance level). That long 
upper wick shows strong selling pressure. 

211
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:57,480
Sellers stepped in when the price got too high.
Again, the inside bar is a small pause. The  

212
00:21:57,480 --> 00:22:01,760
market is stalling, after 
that reaction at resistance. 

213
00:22:01,760 --> 00:22:06,240
A break below the pin bar shows 
supply has taken control. 
  

214
00:22:06,240 --> 00:22:12,040
Remember, the location of the pin bar is crucial.
It should be at a level where the market  

215
00:22:12,040 --> 00:22:17,240
has turned before, or at an 
unmitigated supply or demand. 

216
00:22:17,240 --> 00:22:21,600
And the inside bar adds more 
strength to the pin bar signal. 

217
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:27,760
It shows that the market is confirming the 
potential reversal that the pin bar hinted at.
 
 
  

218
00:22:27,760 --> 00:22:31,440
For a bullish setup:
You enter a buy order,  

219
00:22:31,440 --> 00:22:36,480
just above the high of the pin bar.
You place your stop loss, just below  

220
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:39,320
the low of the pin bar.
And you set your target  

221
00:22:39,320 --> 00:22:44,200
at the next resistance level.
 
The same for a bearish setup: 

222
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:48,320
Enter a sell order just 
below the low of the pin bar. 

223
00:22:48,320 --> 00:22:52,200
You place your stop loss, just 
above the high of the pin bar. 

224
00:22:52,200 --> 00:22:58,680
And you take profit at the next support level.
 
Now, here are some extra tips to make this  

225
00:22:58,680 --> 00:23:03,760
scalping setup even better:
First one is order flow alignment:  

226
00:23:03,760 --> 00:23:08,360
This one is obvious, you try to trade 
in the direction of the bigger trend. 

227
00:23:08,360 --> 00:23:13,680
So check higher time frames, to confirm 
the overall trend and key levels.
  

228
00:23:13,680 --> 00:23:19,000
You also look for other price action signals 
that support your trade. This could be  

229
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:25,240
a trend line break, a chart pattern, 
or confluence with a Fibonacci level. 

230
00:23:25,240 --> 00:23:31,480
And of course, volume: High volume on the 
pin bar, compared to the previous candles,  

231
00:23:31,480 --> 00:23:37,000
will make the signal stronger.
 
 
 
In this specific instance, we see  

232
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:43,560
an uptrend. The price moves up in a series 
of higher highs and higher lows. So, buyers  

233
00:23:43,560 --> 00:23:50,920
are in control. We look for long trades only.
Then, the price hits a support level. A key area  

234
00:23:50,920 --> 00:23:56,240
where buyers have stepped in before.
At this level, we get a pin bar. 

235
00:23:56,240 --> 00:24:02,320
The long lower wick tail shows that sellers 
tried to push the price down, but buyers had  

236
00:24:02,320 --> 00:24:08,800
more power. This quick reversal traps sellers 
who thought the price would keep falling. 

237
00:24:08,800 --> 00:24:15,000
Then we see the inside bar. It fits 
entirely inside the range of the pin bar. 
 
  

238
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:20,880
To trade this, you'd buy when the price 
breaks above the high of the pin bar. 

239
00:24:20,880 --> 00:24:24,680
This break shows that buyers 
are taking control again. 

240
00:24:24,680 --> 00:24:28,120
Your stop loss would go 
below the low of the pin bar. 

241
00:24:28,120 --> 00:24:34,040
This is the "danger point". If price 
falls below here, the setup has failed. 

242
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:39,480
As for target, look for the next 
resistance or supply zones above. 
  

243
00:24:39,480 --> 00:24:43,320
Just remember that this 
setup works best in trends. 

244
00:24:43,320 --> 00:24:49,200
And watch how price acts after the 
breakout. A momentum move up, right away  

245
00:24:49,200 --> 00:24:55,240
after the breakout, is what you want to see.
If it hangs around near the breakout point,  

246
00:24:55,240 --> 00:25:00,400
be cautious. It might not have 
the momentum we hoped for.
 
  

247
00:25:00,400 --> 00:25:04,800
Here’s a short signal.
First, we'd see a downtrend. The price  

248
00:25:04,800 --> 00:25:11,840
moves in a series of lower highs and lower lows.
The price would then hit a resistance level. 

249
00:25:11,840 --> 00:25:17,240
Sellers have stepped in before, so 
it might be a good area to monitor. 

250
00:25:17,240 --> 00:25:23,520
At this resistance, we'd get a pin 
bar. This time, with long upper wick. 

251
00:25:23,520 --> 00:25:28,760
This quick reversal traps buyers who 
thought the price would keep rising. 

252
00:25:28,760 --> 00:25:35,960
Right after the pin bar, we'd see the inside bar.
This combo of pin bar at resistance followed by  

253
00:25:35,960 --> 00:25:42,160
an inside bar is a strong sell signal.
So, we sell when the price breaks below  

254
00:25:42,160 --> 00:25:46,080
the low of the pin bar. 
 
This scalping method gives  

255
00:25:46,080 --> 00:25:50,680
you a structured way to trade.
It combines the power of pin bars  

256
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:55,560
to show potential reversals, with 
the confirmation of inside bars. 

257
00:25:55,560 --> 00:26:00,120
And the breakout entry helps 
you avoid many false signals. 

258
00:26:00,120 --> 00:26:05,400
By waiting for both patterns, you're being 
patient and selective, which is mandatory  

259
00:26:05,400 --> 00:26:28,240
when scalping. You're waiting for the market 
to show its hand before you commit your money. 

260
00:27:31,280 --> 00:27:45,520
Now, if you want to learn other scalping 
methods, go ahead and watch one of these videos.

